<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06320110 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06320110 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Tuckfield  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  FLORIDA; MAN; RESCUE; OCEAN; AVIATION; VEHICLE; ACCIDENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  With a crash survivor under one arm, another survivor and a dog on his back,and two other men in tow, Dan Tuckfield swam for miles to get help after thegroup's plane belly-landed in the ocean off Bimini on its way from Chub Cay toFort Lauderdale, Fla.;   Tuckfield, pilot Brad Youngberg, and Delano Hicks, apassenger, made it. Ira and Dorothy &quot;Dottie&quot; Bloom of Charleston, S.C., andtheir dog died despite Tuckfield's efforts.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  2 FRIENDS, DOG DIE BUT 2 OTHERS SAVED IN AMAZINGRESCUE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     On Thursday, Tuckfield, 35, was in Jackson Memorial Hospital, credited withhelping save Hicks, 58, and Youngberg, 48, by swimming to Cat Cay for helpafter the crash of the twin-engine Piper Seneca on Tuesday.;   Sufferingexposure;   Both Tuckfield and Youngberg were in good condition, sufferingonly from exposure. Hicks was in critical condition with hypothermia, orextremely low body temperature.;   &quot;It was tough, the longest I've ever beenin the water,&quot; he said.;   Tuckfield said he swam at least 30 miles before hereached safety in the Bahamas, according to the Associated Press.;   Obviouslyelated to be alive, he also had somber moments as he recalled the ordeal andthe deaths of the Blooms, who often spent time aboard their 50-foot Hatterasfishing boat at Chub Cay.;   Ira Bloom, 54, had just recovered from cancer andwas weakened by medication. Dottie Bloom, 49, did not know how to swim.;   &quot;Ifelt so bad. They were among my best friends,&quot; said Tuckfield. &quot;They were likefamily.&quot;;   Tuckfield went to Chub Cay because of the Blooms, whom he hadknown for five years. Their boat needed repairs, and he needed to get away fora few days, he said.;   On Tuesday afternoon, Tuckfield, the Blooms and Hicksheaded back to Fort Lauderdale in the Seneca piloted by Youngberg. Also onboard was Chocko, the Blooms' pet Boykin spaniel.;   Engines lose power;   Theplane took off at 4:10 p.m. Twenty-five minutes later, Tuckfield said, theport engine lost power; within minutes the starboard engine failed. Youngbergmade an emergency landing, splashing down 25 miles east of Bimini.;   No onewas hurt. The group had five yellow life vests, but the dog accidentallypunctured one. Tuckfield, a strong swimmer, chose to go without.;   The planesank shortly after the water landing, but the group stayed near it for severalhours. Tuckfield managed to dive down to the plane to retrieve fins, a snorkelmask and a wetsuit.;   At 9 p.m., the group decided to try to swim to shore.Using strips of Velcro from the plane, Tuckfield tied himself to the others.;  &quot;We could see the red tower on Bimini,&quot; said Tuckfield, who swam with DottieBloom and Chocko on his back, and Ira Bloom under his arm.;   But the currentproved too strong, dragging the group to the south. They changed course andheaded for Cat Cay.;   By 7:30 Wednesday morning, Ira Bloom had becomeirrational, ripping off his life vest and letting himself sink under thewater. Tuckfield said he pulled Bloom up and tried to resuscitate him. But itwas too late.;   Tiger shark circles;   Still, Tuckfield held onto hisfriend's motionless body and kept swimming.;   About 1 p.m., he noticed atiger shark circling closer and closer, Tuckfield said. At the same time,Dottie Bloom became delirious, Tuckfield said.;   That's when he let go of IraBloom's body.;   About an hour later, Dottie Bloom &quot;turned white and pale. Shenever came to,&quot; Tuckfield said.;   The Blooms' bodies have not been recovered.A fishing boat picked up two life jackets in the area of the search.;   AfterDottie Bloom died, Tuckfield drowned the dog, who had grown panicky. The threeremaining survivors continued to swim, and at 11 p.m., Tuckfield decided tohead for shore alone.;   &quot;I just swam and swam and swam,&quot; Tuckfield said. &quot;Ikept my mind busy, thinking of my kids and girlfriend. I kept saying I gottamake it.&quot;;   At 7:30 a.m. on Thursday, 38 1/2 hours after the crash, Tuckfieldscrambled ashore on Cat Cay.;   Tuckfield was flown to Jackson MemorialHospital after telling Coast Guard searchers where he had left the other twomen.;   About an hour later, Hicks also made it to shore and was taken toJackson. Youngberg was plucked from the ocean by a Coast Guard helicoptershortly after 9 a.m.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Miami  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911115  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  722  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, November 15, 199100320110,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>